I had a family member tell me recently they were upset with me…. Mind you… it’s not one I speak to of course. 

They were disappointed/mad that I chose to work on Christmas and sent my son to childcare while I did it. Full stop. 
Not only did I NOT send my kid to childcare on Christmas.
I also DID NOT go to work that day. ( turns out I was being spied on and it was obviously the worst spy ever) It was a holiday I took off and I was at home with my family. 
Instead, I was harassed and falsely accused of being away from my child. 
And truthfully…. 
I’m a single mom. If I had to work on Christmas then I had to. 
We need to not shame single moms for WORKING and PROVIDING. A lot of us fill that gap when the other parent cannot. If i was working Christmas then I was working. It just so happened I wasn’t, but if I was… I’m working to provide for my son and that’s the end all be all 💕

I know we all talk a lot of triggers. How to fix them and what causes them etc. As I have gotten older and gained a lot more life experience; I have come to realize that it can really be anything.

This is a bag of chips. If you know me, you know it’s my absolute favorite and I’ve been eating this crap for years. No association to it except it’s a guilty pleasure. 

If you’ve been following me for some time you know that my mom has been fighting cancer. For six months I have spent my Wednesday afternoons at the cancer center with her.

Because of COVID policies ( Yes, still). I am not allowed to sit with her I have to sit in the family lounge. It’s nice enough. There are charging stations, a vending machine, and a soda machine. 

Everyone here is tense. We are all worried. We are all uncertain. I have made friends and I smile and help who I can. 

There is a constant sound of chip bags. It has become a trigger for me. A sign of anxiety. Today I heard the chip bags and I realized we are almost done. It’s a sound I will never want to hear again and I think that healing will take some time. #cancer #cancersucks #fuckcancer

A year ago today, I ended a huge chapter of my life. I told myself I wouldn’t remember the date and I’m strong enough to forget the events that happened to me that night.

The truth is I have dreaded this date. It’s a whole year that I have been diagnosed with PTSD. A whole year of therapy. A whole year of re-arranging friend circles, places I go, and hiding. Hiding firstly because of my son and then to protect my anger.

As much as this day ruined my life and how I see the world, it also saved me. It took me away from a toxic situation. It took me away from unhappiness.It took me away from the thinking that you have to settle. It took me away from abuse. It created a pathway for happiness for me and my son. I have a lot of healing to do and I have been doing my best. I know I’ve come a long way, and I’ll keep going. 

It took one day to save my life. One day of saying enough. One day of knowing I deserve better. Choose your kids and yourself in all situations ❤️
